    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.18.9"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial"><del/><add>9</add></fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        1514 Garfield Avenue
                        Laramie, Wyoming
                        August 15, 1939
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Lincoln, Nebraska</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt.</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I experienced a real thrill when I received your letter last Saturday. Since that time I have re-read the "Song of Hugh Glass". I am acquainted with most of the country of that poem, and I plan to go through parts of it at the close of my summer school session.</p>
                
                <p>I took your letter and the one I received from the University of Nebraska librarian, with a list of the John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt books in the University of Wyoming library , to my major professor, Mr. Coulter, today, and he told me that the study would be too big for a Master's thesis. He said that a Doctor's Dissertation could hardly cover the material adequately.</p> 
                
                <p>I am still determined to continue to give your works a part of my time , even though I shall have to choose another topic for my thesis.</p>
                
                <p>I do not think that Ed Marshall knows that his brother had a part in your works. If you ever care to write to Ed, his address is Glen, Nebraska. He has two children married now.</p>
                
                <p>I am very sorry, Mr. Neihardt, that my major professor feels that you are too big for me, and I feel especially bad that I have disappointed you in this. Should you come through Laramie on your return from the Black Hills I should like to see you.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed>Raymond C. Emery</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
